    overview: 'Studio work at RISD rarely moves in a straight line. Students shift between research, sketching, material testing, fabrication, critique preparation, and presentation, often across multiple projects at once. Existing planning tools tend to be either too rigid for that reality or too generic to support it well.\\\\n\\\\nHow might a planner better support the cadence of studio practice, where progress is iterative, deadlines overlap, and the next step is often unclear?',
    problem: 'Studio students shift between research, sketching, material testing, fabrication, critique prep, and presentation—often across multiple projects at once. Existing planning tools are either too rigid or too generic. Creative progress loops through revision, assignments overlap, and coordination with peers and faculty introduces waiting periods. Students could track individual tasks but struggled to see the state of a project as a whole.',
    process: 'I interviewed 8+ RISD students across studio-based disciplines to understand how they organize projects and where planning breaks down. Four themes emerged: scattered reference material, uncertainty about next steps, delays caused by coordination, and overwhelm from too many unresolved tasks. I used affinity mapping to synthesize insights around momentum tracking, stage-based thinking, and surfacing "what\'s next" without adding stress.',
